20
00:01:17,486 --> 00:01:19,988
and define some key questions and action steps.

21
00:01:20,269 --> 00:01:36,704
So we will walk through the outline proposed ordinance, walk through research from Lily from the PDS department, talk about some of the specific goals for the ordinance, and hone how we will achieve those goals through legislative language.

22
00:01:37,185 --> 00:01:39,667
And with that, I will turn it over to Councilor Collins.

23
00:01:40,893 --> 00:01:42,053
Great, thank you very much.

24
00:01:44,354 --> 00:02:06,860
So just to quickly set the table since it's been, I think since March, since we last met on this paper, I'm sure that we all remember the key ingredients of this ordinance, but for any residents who may be watching or just learning about this for the first time, a condo conversion ordinance is a legislative mechanism that allows us to regulate

25
00:02:08,128 --> 00:02:13,453
what happens and under what conditions rental units are converted into condos.

26
00:02:13,693 --> 00:02:23,721
And there's a state version of this ordinance that sets the floor in terms of how that can happen and how it should look and what protections exist for tenants when that happens.

27
00:02:24,362 --> 00:02:36,272
And then many, many municipalities in Massachusetts have instituted local ordinances recently and also over the past several decades to build upon those to increase protections for tenants,

28
00:02:36,718 --> 00:02:40,341
to evolve with the times.

29
00:02:44,264 --> 00:03:03,299
The reason that this I think has come up regionally and also nationally as well as regionally, and the reason that I think it's relevant to us in our community as it is to many neighboring communities, we know, it's documented here in Medford that we have a pretty severe scarcity of

30
00:03:03,907 --> 00:03:06,589
rental units, we have a scarcity of certain types of rental units.

31
00:03:08,151 --> 00:03:13,575
And of course, you know, every type of housing has its place in the ecosystem, ecosystem of housing in Medford.

32
00:03:14,116 --> 00:03:22,082
But it's important to put up safeguards proactively, so that when there are incentives for for profit developers to

33
00:03:23,057 --> 00:03:36,500
quote unquote cash in on rental units or to speculatively invest in condo units, you know, essentially to extract value from what was our share of rental units, that the community gets something out of that as well.

34
00:03:37,320 --> 00:03:44,562
Because it is a harm to communities when rental units are taken off the table, especially when they're, you know, in very high demand to begin with, which is the case here in Medford.

35
00:03:45,502 --> 00:03:47,563
So we're essentially, this is essentially a way to,

36
00:03:48,680 --> 00:04:13,473
look at that issue and say, okay, when for-profit developers want to extract value out of our rental unit market, when they take rental units off the table here in Medford, here's how that has to go for it to be fair and to contend with displacement of tenants that results from that, and also to make sure that the community writ large gets something out of that, not just the for-profit developers making a profit off of it.

37
00:04:14,134 --> 00:04:15,495
So that's just a really quick overview

38
00:04:17,033 --> 00:04:18,975
why we're meeting on this to begin with.

39
00:04:20,977 --> 00:04:27,143
I'll quickly walk through an outline of the ordinance.

40
00:04:28,084 --> 00:04:35,391
When I did my initial research back in March, I found that all of the local condo conversion ordinances followed a really, really similar formula.

41
00:04:35,871 --> 00:04:38,274
So that presents a really helpful starting place for us.

42
00:04:40,655 --> 00:04:51,061
Most of them include a statement of intent or purpose section, they define all of the relevant terms, and then come in the requirements for what happens during a condo conversion.

43
00:04:51,962 --> 00:05:01,607
The main parts of that are notice requirements, how much notice to give to tenants for what types of tenants, if there are different conditions for occupied units, unoccupied units.

44
00:05:03,008 --> 00:05:08,191
All of these ordinances articulate different conditions for protected tenants,

45
00:05:08,951 --> 00:05:14,174
which means elderly tenants, disabled tenants, or low to moderate income tenants.

46
00:05:14,294 --> 00:05:35,405
This section will also cover how to rent units while conversion is going on, a prohibition on evicting people simply because the conversion is going on, tenant first right of refusal, city first right of refusal, and then relocation payments to the displaced tenants, relocation assistance to the displaced tenants,

47
00:05:37,345 --> 00:05:49,616
as well as other things we might include, such as a number of conversions being capped at a certain number per year per developer, renovations during a notice period, and the tenant's right to vacate during the conversion.

48
00:05:50,857 --> 00:06:01,427
Finally, this also goes over the establishment of a review board that, you know, this is the board through which all of this permitting and requirements are done through.

49
00:06:04,537 --> 00:06:07,439
So that's the general structure that we've been working with.

50
00:06:07,479 --> 00:06:22,267
And as for our next steps, I've gone through and kind of highlighted the parts in that overall table of contents where we have some decisions to make, where certain cities split off from others in terms of how long is the notice period?

51
00:06:22,847 --> 00:06:25,489
Is there a cap on number of conversions per developer?

52
00:06:26,189 --> 00:06:27,490
Is there a tenant right to purchase?

53
00:06:27,550 --> 00:06:29,431
And how long is that time period, et cetera?

54
00:06:30,632 --> 00:06:32,453
So what I'd like to do next is,

55
00:06:33,447 --> 00:06:42,874
walk through some of the other research that we've done since our first meeting, and then we can come back and flag some of those decision points and start having a conversation about how to write our version of this ordinance.

56
