169
00:19:15,474 --> 00:19:16,954
So kind of going top to bottom.

170
00:19:19,095 --> 00:19:25,377
The first section in sort of procedures for common conversion in these ordinances is usually notice requirements.

171
00:19:26,437 --> 00:19:30,339
And this means, okay, you've filed your conversion permit,

172
00:19:32,045 --> 00:19:38,828
a owner and you say, I want to develop this into a condo, you file your permit with the city, what happens then?

173
00:19:40,068 --> 00:19:45,370
So the state law regulating condo conversions kind of sets the basement floor here.

174
00:19:47,892 --> 00:19:56,415
And with saying it's two years, so the state set floor for the notice requirements is you have to give protected tenants two years to vacate.

175
00:19:57,027 --> 00:19:59,668
get to stay in their home for two years before they have to vacate.

176
00:20:00,288 --> 00:20:02,388
And all other tenants, they get one year.

177
00:20:02,828 --> 00:20:24,034
So that's kind of, you know, the bare bones, we're looking to what other communities have done is build upon that and say, okay, that can be a little especially in this type of housing environment, when we know that our vacancy rates are really, really low, that is not really adequate to find suitable, comparable housing, especially in the same community.

178
00:20:24,754 --> 00:20:25,134
So what

179
00:20:25,827 --> 00:20:32,908
is most typical in the local ordinances that we studied is that protected tenants are given five years of notice before they have to vacate.

180
00:20:32,928 --> 00:20:43,731
And all other tenants are given one year to vacate, although there is an exception, Marlborough extends notice to non-protected tenants for three years.

181
00:20:45,751 --> 00:20:49,672
So I think that's a good jumping off point for this kind of first deliberation point.

182
00:20:51,473 --> 00:20:59,435
If we were to align with most other communities, that would be adopting a five-year notice period for protected tenants and a one-year notice period for all other tenants.

183
00:21:00,095 --> 00:21:11,078
Or we could decide to align with our more proactive local communities that have this ordinance and say, well, why not three?

184
00:21:11,378 --> 00:21:16,459
What's the argument for not going for three years in a time of housing scarcity?

185
00:21:16,539 --> 00:21:20,980
And when we know experientially how hard it is to stay in the city, you really need a lot of time to make that happen.

186
00:21:26,783 --> 00:21:30,745
I guess I don't have to raise my hand, but just a question on that.

187
00:21:33,666 --> 00:21:35,507
Is the notice period the same as the waiting period?

188
00:21:37,408 --> 00:21:37,668
No.

189
00:21:37,688 --> 00:21:38,169
Okay.

190
00:21:39,009 --> 00:21:43,972
The waiting period is, I'm not sure what other communities have this other than Boston.

191
00:21:44,672 --> 00:21:50,795
In Boston, the waiting period is like year long holding period before the notice period starts.

192
00:21:51,575 --> 00:21:54,457
I believe the reason that Boston did that is so that

193
00:21:56,669 --> 00:21:58,135
Let me see if I can phrase this correctly.

194
00:22:02,295 --> 00:22:25,509
I don't have the mechanism for this right at the tip of my tongue, but I think that was put up as a way to, they were seeing in City of Boston, developers were just empty, they knew that they wanted to convert to condos, they would just empty out the building so that there would be no tenants present so that they wouldn't have to deal with the issue of relocation payments or relocation assistance when they did file the intent to convert to condos.

195
00:22:26,630 --> 00:22:29,412
The waiting period was an attempt to disincentivize

196
00:22:30,729 --> 00:22:30,989
that.

197
00:22:31,730 --> 00:22:33,891
So that's separate.

198
00:22:34,991 --> 00:22:45,137
For myself, if the state's already setting a floor and the point of the policy is that the state law is not sufficient, I think we should consider going above the minimum.

199
00:22:47,898 --> 00:22:48,999
I would tend to agree.

200
00:22:49,279 --> 00:22:55,903
I hope that we can get to a version of this ordinance where the notice period is not less than two years.

201
00:22:56,598 --> 00:23:05,165
for all tenants I think that starting with the Marlboro model of 5 years for protected monitor for protected tenants and 3 years for all of the tenants would be a great place to start.

202
00:23:19,376 --> 00:23:21,578
Then on the issue of the waiting period.

203
00:23:21,598 --> 00:23:23,960
I think that's something that I might want to

204
00:23:24,844 --> 00:23:32,969
do a little additional research on or check in with our PDS department about prior to our next meeting, just to better understand how that might be useful.

205
00:23:40,114 --> 00:23:47,779
So moving on, just because there's a lot to cover, but happy to pause anywhere.

206
00:23:51,563 --> 00:23:56,308
Next in the table of contents is the tenant right to purchase or first red refusal.

207
00:23:57,169 --> 00:24:01,393
This is present in most of the other ordinances that we studied.

208
00:24:01,433 --> 00:24:12,304
I think that having this mechanism in our ordinance is really aligned with the goal of trying to keep Medford residents in Medford and making sure that when a condo is created out of a rental unit,

209
00:24:13,180 --> 00:24:18,803
I think that there's no reason to at least offer the opportunity to purchase that condo to the person who's already made it their home.

210
00:24:19,763 --> 00:24:34,309
So the thing to decide here is, one, whether to include this at all, but I think we absolutely should, is the time interval offered, the sort of the window of time in which a tenant can, like has the option to say, okay, I put up my hand, you know, sell it to me.

211
00:24:35,049 --> 00:24:40,512
And of course there are additional requirements around this, that it has to be aligned with the,

212
00:24:42,779 --> 00:24:49,101
you know, the market rate that the seller could otherwise get for the condo if they were to put it on the market.

213
00:24:50,381 --> 00:25:00,245
In most communities, protected tenants get a 180 day window to exercise their right of first refusal and all other tenants get 120 days.

214
00:25:01,185 --> 00:25:04,446
So that's like four months and six months.

215
00:25:07,052 --> 00:25:11,294
I think that the benefit to starting here is that would give us parity with Somerville.

216
00:25:11,995 --> 00:25:23,520
And I haven't been able to do the research to know if this is true, but I would imagine that the developers operating at Somerville are going to be looking at the other side of that border as well.

217
00:25:24,481 --> 00:25:34,646
So I think it makes sense to try to align to make sure that we don't become, you know, I would hate for our rental environment to just be more fertile ground for for-profit developers.

218
00:25:49,941 --> 00:25:51,222
Thumbs up.

219
00:25:51,582 --> 00:26:00,629
Next, we get to the city first right of refusal, and this is actually something that I think we might need to refer out for legal confirmation.

220
00:26:00,649 --> 00:26:05,573
I believe many of the ordinances that we looked at had

221
00:26:05,973 --> 00:26:18,183
a city right of first refusal, so exactly the same as a tenant right of first refusal, only if the tenant says no thank you, then it goes to the city to say we would like to purchase that, or the city designee, so maybe that's an affordable housing trust.

222
00:26:20,164 --> 00:26:30,513
Recently, in the past several years, Somerville updated their ordinance to include a city right of first refusal, and that was invalidated by the courts.

223
00:26:31,253 --> 00:26:33,195
So I think,

224
00:26:35,042 --> 00:26:37,424
It would be nice if that was possible, but it seems like it might not be.

225
00:26:37,704 --> 00:26:43,708
So I would probably like to have that commented on by KP Law to see if it's worth us pursuing.

226
00:26:48,392 --> 00:26:50,433
Lily, you were nodding like you know something about this.

227
00:26:54,796 --> 00:26:59,720
Yes, I did speak to one of the staff members in Somerville who staffs the Condo Review Board.

228
00:26:59,760 --> 00:27:03,022
And she mentioned that because it had been challenged in court, they were removing that.

229
00:27:03,884 --> 00:27:09,586
provision, but I think that's something that they definitely were hoping to implement in the future if possible.

230
00:27:09,626 --> 00:27:13,347
And I'm not really sure what the legal grounds for that was, unfortunately.

231
00:27:14,988 --> 00:27:15,288
Thank you.

232
00:27:15,608 --> 00:27:18,188
If I had to soft guess, I'm guessing it's an illegal taking.

233
00:27:18,209 --> 00:27:21,830
It's kind of eminent domain-y.

234
00:27:23,670 --> 00:27:25,531
Yeah, it's in like an eminent domain realm.

235
00:27:25,971 --> 00:27:26,151
Yeah.

236
00:27:30,132 --> 00:27:30,372
Great.

237
00:27:30,872 --> 00:27:32,733
Well, moving right along, so we'll follow up on that.

238
00:27:33,666 --> 00:27:36,147
Moving along to relocation payments.

239
00:27:36,647 --> 00:27:51,852
So this is another condition that is present in the state condo conversion requirements that sets the floor, and it's present in every community that has a local condo conversion ordinance.

240
00:27:54,893 --> 00:27:59,234
So just to draw on again, the example of a couple of our close neighbors in Somerville.

241
00:27:59,874 --> 00:28:01,655
Oh, and so the relocation payment is,

242
00:28:03,490 --> 00:28:05,931
So an owner says, I'm going to convert this into a condo.

243
00:28:05,951 --> 00:28:07,432
They file with the condo review board.

244
00:28:08,632 --> 00:28:09,753
They send out the notice.

245
00:28:10,393 --> 00:28:11,714
Maybe they offer it to the tenant.

246
00:28:12,134 --> 00:28:14,175
If they want to purchase it, the tenant says, no, thank you.

247
00:28:14,995 --> 00:28:25,420
Then in addition to the other requirements, they have to pay a relocation payment to the tenant that will be forced to vacate the unit because it's going to be converted to a condo.

248
00:28:28,362 --> 00:28:30,763
And I just want to note for anybody who maybe didn't attend

249
00:28:31,230 --> 00:28:55,265
our first meeting or doesn't know a lot about this, I can hear the argument in my head of like, oh, so like, this is just a payment that goes to a tenant, like, no matter what, like this, there are, there's protection, sorry, there's a protection to tenants for not, that they can't be evicted for reasons explicitly related to conversion.

250
00:28:56,866 --> 00:28:59,348
All other housing rules still apply in this case.

251
00:28:59,708 --> 00:29:03,590
Like for example, I'm sure there are many things that people can do that warrant eviction.

252
00:29:04,471 --> 00:29:06,993
Just being present while a conversion going on is not one of them.

253
00:29:08,814 --> 00:29:25,545
So of course, if outlandish things were to occur and a tenant needed to be vacated of the premises, this ordinance wouldn't prevent that, but all else being equal, a tenant cannot be removed from a unit just because a conversion is going to go on and they would be owed

254
00:29:26,410 --> 00:29:31,512
a relocation payment, like essentially as compensation for being forced out because of the conversion.

255
00:29:32,492 --> 00:29:36,033
So just to explain that before I go further.

256
00:29:39,475 --> 00:29:45,297
So in Somerville, the relocation payment is $10,000 for protected tenants and $6,000 for all other tenants.

257
00:29:45,317 --> 00:29:47,938
In Boston, it's a good amount higher.

258
00:29:47,998 --> 00:29:49,278
It's $15,000 for protected tenants.

259
00:29:56,072 --> 00:29:58,695
$10,000 for all other tenants.

260
00:30:00,236 --> 00:30:03,880
And here there's an exemption if the tenant does, you know, opt in to purchase the unit.

261
00:30:05,321 --> 00:30:12,128
Again, I think that striving for parity with our neighbors is important, one because like rental pricing is at this point, very, very comparable.

262
00:30:20,212 --> 00:30:29,295
Another concern I had going into this section is, you know, as we know this from many of our other ordinances in the city, it's fine to set like a dollar amount in year 2023, but what about 2030?

263
00:30:29,636 --> 00:30:30,576
What about 2045?

264
00:30:33,617 --> 00:30:46,042
Several of our neighbors ordinances articulate that the dollar amount, whatever dollar amount is set for the relocation payment is adjusted annually according to the consumer price index.

265
00:30:47,411 --> 00:31:01,238
And I think that regardless of the number that we settle on, I think it's very important that the relocation payment not have to be amended by a legislative process, but rather be something that evolves every year automatically.

266
00:31:06,200 --> 00:31:13,424
On that point, would it be possible for us to kind of, I mean, I see that there's a potential,

267
00:31:15,683 --> 00:31:21,507
inflationary adjustment, would it be possible for us to tie this directly to median rent?

268
00:31:23,368 --> 00:31:30,772
Like, most if you have to rent, you usually have to pay, you know, first, last security and a broker's fee.

269
00:31:30,832 --> 00:31:40,138
So maybe four times the median monthly rent adjusted, you know, something like that, we could try to pick whatever we think is the most accurate measure.

270
00:31:44,594 --> 00:31:50,337
Because I think if we were using inflationary adjustments, we would underestimate rent increases.

271
00:31:52,898 --> 00:31:54,219
Yeah, I think that's a great point.

272
00:31:56,360 --> 00:32:07,286
I think that it probably would be more accurate to have the time to have it be equal to four times whatever median rent is at the beginning of the year or some other way of benchmarking that.

273
00:32:08,966 --> 00:32:09,887
Probably better than CPI.

274
00:32:11,020 --> 00:32:15,203
And then there could maybe be some sort of specific addition for protected tenants above that.

275
00:32:17,545 --> 00:32:18,225
I could see that.

276
00:32:19,386 --> 00:32:25,870
I think doing the formula that way really ties to the intended purpose.

277
00:32:26,091 --> 00:32:31,034
It's basically calculating what we think relocation cost is.

278
00:32:31,114 --> 00:32:33,156
And the 6,000, the 10,000, the 10,000, the 15,000 numbers are probably somewhere in that range, right?

279
00:32:33,196 --> 00:32:33,676
But this would...

280
00:32:40,200 --> 00:32:42,181
be able to narrow us in a little bit more.

281
00:32:43,142 --> 00:33:05,996
And I think, you know, it captures the spirit of why there would be a difference for protected tenants and non-protected tenants in that protected tenants may spend more time seeking, you know, a unit that they can access and then could use the additional funds for temporary short-term housing if necessary.

282
00:33:12,198 --> 00:33:14,120
Yeah, I think that's a great line of thinking.

283
00:33:17,444 --> 00:33:27,815
Maybe a way to articulate that is all tenants, four times median rent, and then maybe a percentage adjustment for protected tenants.

284
00:33:28,596 --> 00:33:34,462
Yeah, or a stipend or even, yeah, something like that, but yeah.

285
00:33:42,787 --> 00:33:42,987
Great.

286
00:33:44,727 --> 00:33:53,289
I think that thinking through what that could look like could be a great thing for us to circulate for feedback and do a little bit more research on before our next meeting.

287
00:33:53,389 --> 00:33:56,250
I think that's a really important part of this to get right.

288
00:33:56,270 --> 00:33:58,891
Awesome.

289
00:34:03,472 --> 00:34:07,833
Any other thoughts on this piece before we move on to relocation assistance?

290
00:34:11,314 --> 00:34:12,154
Not for me, thank you.

291
00:34:16,110 --> 00:34:24,034
So relocation assistance is the other direct benefit afforded to tenants that are present while their unit is being converted into a condo.

292
00:34:25,635 --> 00:34:29,397
And all of the examples that I've looked at, it's extended only to protected tenants.

293
00:34:32,679 --> 00:34:41,043
If a owner or their designee fails to find suitable, comparable new housing in the same community, it extends the notice period by an additional two years.

294
00:34:43,252 --> 00:34:49,174
So this is something where I'm weighing, is this sufficient to adopt?

295
00:34:50,054 --> 00:34:56,376
Should we seek to extend relocation assistance to all tenants and then step it up for protected tenants?

296
00:35:01,497 --> 00:35:05,098
Quickly look over my comparison from our last meeting.

297
00:35:12,848 --> 00:35:18,352
I think generally how this has been handled in other communities, and Lily, if you've heard otherwise, please correct me.

298
00:35:19,433 --> 00:35:26,819
I don't know of any examples of relocation assistance being extended to non-protected tenants.

299
00:35:28,079 --> 00:35:30,661
So if we were to consider that, we would be pioneers in the field.

300
00:35:32,643 --> 00:35:34,124
Mechanically, what does this look like?

301
00:35:34,184 --> 00:35:37,627
Is it connecting them with a realtor?

302
00:35:40,827 --> 00:35:46,170
Based on what I know, it seems like it's left up to the owner.

303
00:35:47,571 --> 00:35:53,095
In the text that I've read, it was just that the property owner shall assist.

304
00:35:53,655 --> 00:35:58,458
And I'm sure in a lot of cases, that means just liaising and setting up your tenant with

305
00:35:59,490 --> 00:36:03,513
broker or maybe with somebody from the city or putting them in touch with resources.

306
00:36:05,614 --> 00:36:07,456
Who determines failure to assist?

307
00:36:07,756 --> 00:36:16,102
I just think we should maybe try to go beyond maybe what other communities have done here and be a little more concrete.

308
00:36:16,762 --> 00:36:25,649
Sorry, I'm saying I think we should go beyond what the other communities ordinances have done here and try to be a little more concrete because

309
00:36:27,378 --> 00:36:33,962
If assistance isn't described or defined in any way, I think it's difficult to determine a failure to assist.

310
00:36:34,502 --> 00:36:41,647
So I'd be interested in how communities define that, who have passed these ordinances.

311
00:36:42,607 --> 00:36:44,429
And if they don't, I think we should try to.

312
00:36:46,470 --> 00:36:47,470
Yeah, I agree with that.

313
00:36:47,510 --> 00:36:50,352
I think it's important to make it really clear.

314
00:36:52,018 --> 00:36:55,579
at the ordinance level, what failure looks like and also what helping looks like.

315
00:36:55,599 --> 00:37:04,301
Because otherwise, I think that what implementation of this looks like depends on, like, first of all, what the condo review board looks like and who's staffing it.

316
00:37:11,443 --> 00:37:15,824
I wouldn't be surprised if in a lot of cases, this is determination of this is just left up to the condo review board.

317
00:37:18,544 --> 00:37:20,705
But I think it would be great to know

318
00:37:22,421 --> 00:37:28,304
more about what's been done so that we can work more of that language into here.

319
00:37:28,324 --> 00:37:51,698
I wouldn't want to go overly prescriptive with what the assistance has to look like, but maybe a good place to start here would be reaching out to the other communities that have this ordinance currently operating, trying to hear directly from their condo review boards, Office of Housing Stabilities, to learn more about what it looks like and what we might want to explicitly adopt.

320
00:37:53,625 --> 00:38:03,051
even if they just have definitions in a kind of ruby board regulation somewhere around, you know, OHS policy, I think that would be sufficient.

321
00:38:27,201 --> 00:38:49,465
Awesome, I think that's a... And then since we mentioned going beyond the kind of sample language that we're looking at, well, maybe learning more about what implementation of this has looked like in other communities will inform, if it's feasible, what it could look like to extend it to all tenants and not just protected tenants.

322
00:38:58,892 --> 00:39:01,554
Okay, proceeding right along.

323
00:39:01,574 --> 00:39:11,541
Next to talk about is if the number of conversions per developer per year should be limited.

324
00:39:12,742 --> 00:39:21,488
Some examples of caps that communities have put up in Marlborough, no more than 25% of units in a building may be converted per year.

325
00:39:23,249 --> 00:39:27,973
In Lexington, there's no numerical cap specified, but conversion licenses

326
00:39:29,224 --> 00:39:37,091
may or may not be issued according to public interest as determined by their condo review board and how aggravated the rental shortages.

327
00:39:40,693 --> 00:39:52,703
I also want to note that the way Malden has handled condo conversions is to on certain types of buildings on 2 to 3 unit buildings conversions are explicitly not allowed

328
00:39:54,575 --> 00:39:59,758
unless the vacancy rate is higher than 3.5%, which is kind of an interesting way of handling the problem, I think.

329
00:39:59,778 --> 00:40:06,102
It's a way of saying like, okay, if we're really hard up for rentals, you can't convert, sorry, they have to stay rentals.

330
00:40:06,662 --> 00:40:11,125
If there's not a lot of demand for rentals, then they let some more through the gate.

331
00:40:12,126 --> 00:40:13,446
I think it's an interesting mechanism.

332
00:40:13,527 --> 00:40:19,490
It worries me a little bit because of the ebb and flow of vacancy rates.

333
00:40:20,511 --> 00:40:24,113
And we can't really control for,

334
00:40:25,748 --> 00:40:29,409
you know, how many rentals will enter the market in the future, if a lot of them do get converted.

335
00:40:32,790 --> 00:40:39,912
So I think that there's a couple questions under this section, which is, are we putting a numerical cap on?

336
00:40:39,932 --> 00:40:43,053
Are we interested in putting a numerical cap on at all?

337
00:40:44,954 --> 00:40:49,175
Is that number of units in a building, percentage of units in a building?

338
00:40:49,315 --> 00:40:52,796
Is it how many conversion permits

339
00:40:53,719 --> 00:40:56,761
are permitted at all based on community conditions.

340
00:40:57,641 --> 00:41:03,585
Is it based on conversion permits will be issued for certain types of buildings, but not other types of buildings?

341
00:41:13,852 --> 00:41:21,156
I think one thing that is interesting to me, I think that this whole section I'd like to get a lot more feedback on from department heads.

342
00:41:23,885 --> 00:41:41,475
But kind of in conjunction with the conversation around what our condo review board would look like, I'm kind of interested in the Lexington example of there not being a hard and fast numerical cap, but whether or not a conversion license can be issued is subject to the conditions on the ground when it's sought.

343
00:41:41,495 --> 00:41:43,397
I think it's potentially problematic.

344
00:41:43,457 --> 00:41:52,582
It's potentially, I don't know how many denials that would actually result in at the end of the day.

345
00:41:54,223 --> 00:42:11,467
But I will say I'm wary about exempting smaller buildings entirely from this ordinance because so much of our rental environment is smaller buildings and not these big unit buildings that you do see in cities like Boston.

346
00:42:15,908 --> 00:42:20,009
Yeah, on this point, for me, I think

347
00:42:22,622 --> 00:42:29,126
given our housing stock, it would be unwise to exclude two and three families.

348
00:42:33,628 --> 00:42:42,893
Given Lily's research, I wonder if it would make sense to, or even if it would be possible to perhaps have an owner-occupied

349
00:42:44,057 --> 00:43:09,306
exemption for two and three families where if someone who lives in a building and intends to stay in one of the units, maybe the second, maybe not even intends to stay in one of the units, but essentially since most of the condo conversions are happening by flippers, you know, if one out of every 50 condo conversions is someone who owns a two family and wants to convert,

350
00:43:10,367 --> 00:43:16,810
maybe we should treat that differently than we treat the other 49, which are, you know, flips.

351
00:43:19,691 --> 00:43:22,292
And limit conversions per building per year.

352
00:43:22,332 --> 00:43:31,315
Does that more apply to the larger buildings where it's like, if you have 40 units, you can only do a certain, okay.

353
00:43:31,495 --> 00:43:38,018
Yeah, because, so I think that would have to be, we'd have to have a regime for anything four plus and anything,

354
00:43:39,472 --> 00:43:40,193
under four.

355
00:43:43,915 --> 00:44:08,133
Then I guess my question on the vacancy rate is, you know, who's calculating it and how, and I want to see historical vacancy rate data, which may not exist if I would, you know, if we historically have had 5% vacancy rates, but in the last 10 years, it's been closer to 1% vacancy rates that reflects the increase in demand, you know, that would inform my thinking.

356
00:44:09,199 --> 00:44:13,503
around using the vacancy rate metric.

357
00:44:15,445 --> 00:44:19,749
And then we just want to know if it was reliable to, or if we're estimating it, or if we're using a regional measure.

358
00:44:21,491 --> 00:44:23,533
All of those I think are impactful.

359
00:44:29,578 --> 00:44:32,001
Yeah, I think those are very relevant questions.

360
00:44:48,068 --> 00:44:49,469
All right, no need for a motion.

361
00:44:49,509 --> 00:44:51,631
We are picking back up where we left off.

362
00:44:52,412 --> 00:44:53,453
Councilor Collins.

363
00:44:54,253 --> 00:44:54,554
Great.

364
00:44:55,554 --> 00:45:11,227
Well, I think that we were just tying off our discussion of how to potentially limit the number of conversions, but I think it was sort of morphing into a discussion of how to separately treat

365
00:45:12,694 --> 00:45:20,961
small buildings versus large buildings, apartment buildings with many units, and how to work in an owner-occupied exemption.

366
00:45:20,981 --> 00:45:31,130
And I think that one of my biggest question marks in this is we say that we want to make sure that we're targeting flippers, for-profit developers, not targeting owner-occupiers.

367
00:45:32,511 --> 00:45:34,392
And I think that this is a really important part of this.

368
00:45:36,034 --> 00:45:40,457
And it sounds like maybe where that will figure in will be maybe mostly housed in this section.

369
00:45:44,399 --> 00:46:12,130
I think where we're coming out of this is that we're disinclined to exempt two to three unit buildings because that's such a large percentage of rentals in Medford in general, but that there should be some sort of exemption for that type of building where the owner is, you know, has lived there and maybe will remain to live there or maybe not, but will retain ownership as opposed to selling to a for-profit company, selling to a flipper.

370
00:46:13,848 --> 00:46:26,754
And I think that's, I think this will be a great thing to bring to department heads, Commissioner Fordy, do some more research on to figure out sort of exact language for how to achieve that in the text.

371
00:46:29,976 --> 00:46:39,580
So the last major piece that I thought we ought to talk about tonight that we could formulate some next steps and research around is the establishment of a condo review board.

372
00:46:42,561 --> 00:46:43,402
So this would be,

373
00:46:45,182 --> 00:46:56,948
you know, the board that would receive the applications, the condo licenses, would grant the condo permits, would also be the overseer for, are you actually following this ordinance or are you breaking the rules?

374
00:46:58,189 --> 00:47:02,091
This is sort of the implementing body for the ordinance.

375
00:47:02,972 --> 00:47:07,314
So in other communities, this ordinance has established an independent condo review board.

376
00:47:08,014 --> 00:47:13,177
In other communities, it's been sort of a joint project between the Office of Housing Stability and Inspectional Services.

377
00:47:16,002 --> 00:47:23,088
or I would say in most communities, they set up a condo review board since, or I guess, and that's what Somerville did.

378
00:47:24,329 --> 00:47:27,232
Boston, it's their OHS and inspectional services.

379
00:47:27,252 --> 00:47:42,285
I think in Marlborough, it is a collaboration between the mayor's office, their community development authority, and the city council.

380
00:47:46,033 --> 00:47:53,217
I feel like it looms pretty large for me that we don't have a lot of extra capacity in Medford right now to be setting up additional boards.

381
00:47:53,297 --> 00:47:57,220
We have a lot of vacant positions on our existing boards.

382
00:47:57,260 --> 00:48:03,463
I think this is one where like some fairly technical knowledge is involved.

383
00:48:04,784 --> 00:48:10,167
And so I'm a little bit skeptical about the success of sending up an independent condo review board.

384
00:48:10,187 --> 00:48:13,069
I mean, if the city has the resources to really support that board

385
00:48:14,089 --> 00:48:15,111
implementing this ordinance.

386
00:48:15,551 --> 00:48:17,914
Maybe that's too pessimistic, I'm not sure.

387
00:48:18,455 --> 00:48:27,948
So I think the question is, do we want to talk further about that, establishing a condo review board, which could be staffed by, I think, in other communities.

388
00:48:28,229 --> 00:48:30,211
I think the example I'm thinking of is Somerville.

389
00:48:31,920 --> 00:48:43,722
And I think it's a combination of city staff, homeowners, tenants, and tenants in that protected class, all members of Somerville, sorry, residents of Somerville.

390
00:48:44,562 --> 00:48:46,103
That's kind of the formulation.

391
00:48:47,183 --> 00:48:57,265
Do we want to see, talk about going that route, or should we talk about tasking an existing department or board with these responsibilities?

392
00:49:03,030 --> 00:49:05,753
My recommendation here would be that we ask the Community Development Board.

393
00:49:08,675 --> 00:49:09,696
